look around

You and Marcus leave the village behind, heading east along the path Bram indicated. The dense canopy of the ancient forest quickly swallows the open sky, and the air grows cooler. Dappled sunlight filters through the leaves, painting shifting patterns on the forest floor. The only sounds are the crunch of your boots on dry leaves, the distant call of a bird, and the quiet, professional watchfulness of your new companion. Marcus walks with his hand resting near the hilt of his greatsword, his eyes constantly scanning the trees.

The path is clear, but the woods on either side are thick with undergrowth and deep shadows. It's easy to see how a goblin patrol could lay an ambush here. You decide to take a more careful look at your surroundings, searching for any signs of recent passage or potential danger.

[ROLL: Perception DC 12]As you scan the area, your eyes adjust to the dim light. Most of the forest floor is a chaotic mess of fallen leaves, but your focused search pays off. Just off the main path, you spot a series of small, clumsy footprints in a patch of damp earth. They're clearly not from any normal animal, and the shoddy make of the boot prints screams 'goblin'.

Following the trail with your eyes, you see more signs: a snapped twig here, an overturned rock there. More disturbingly, you notice a long, continuous drag mark through the leaves, as if something‚Äîor someone‚Äîwas being pulled along against their will. The tracks lead deeper into the woods, paralleling the main path before veering off further to the east.

Marcus notices you've stopped and follows your gaze. He grunts in confirmation. "Goblins, alright. More than a few, by the looks of it. And in a hurry." He points with his chin at the drag mark. "Looks like we're on the right trail. They're heading deeper into the forest, toward the caves." He looks to you, his hand resting on his sword's pommel. "Best be on our guard. No telling what's waiting up ahead." The path continues east, following the goblin tracks.

üé≤ Perception Check (DC 12): rolled 14 +2 = 16 ‚úÖYour keen eyes pick up more than just the obvious trail. As you crouch down for a closer look, you notice the disturbed earth around the footprints is still dark and damp; these tracks are fresh, no more than a few hours old. The drag mark tells its own grim story‚Äîit's uneven, with scuffs and deeper gouges in the dirt where Lily must have tried to dig in her heels and fight back.

Then, you spot it: a tiny shred of pale blue, homespun cloth snagged on the thorns of a nearby bush. It's a small, easily missed detail, but it confirms someone was dragged this way against their will. It looks like the kind of simple fabric a farmer's daughter might wear.

Marcus follows your gaze to the scrap of cloth and lets out a low whistle. "Good eye," he says, his voice losing its sarcastic edge for a moment. "So, she's a fighter. And they're not far ahead." He draws his greatsword, the rasp of steel on leather unnervingly loud in the quiet forest. "No more strolling. We move carefully from here on out." The path, and the fresh goblin tracks, lead directly east, deeper into the increasingly gloomy woods.

